          "content": "### THE CABINET ROOM\n\nThe Executive Committee (ExComm) has been meeting in continuous, secret session. The atmosphere is thick with exhaust and fear. The table is a battlefield of conflicting ideologies, and the President is the referee. \n\n**The Three Options:**\n1.  **Do Nothing:** Accept the missiles as a new reality, just as the Europeans live with Soviet missiles pointed at them. (Rejected immediately as political suicide).\n2.  **Airstrike (OPLAN 312):** A swift, overwhelming military blow to knock out the threat before it becomes operational.\n3.  **The Blockade:** A naval cordon to stop further shipments. Secretary of Defense McNamara champions this as a middle ground. It buys time. It forces Khrushchev to make the next move. It avoids immediate bloodshed.\n\n**The Guns of August:**\nPresident Kennedy is haunted by Barbara Tuchman's book *The Guns of August*, which describes how the Great Powers stumbled into World War I through miscalculation and rigid military schedules. He is terrified that a 'small' airstrike could trigger a chain reaction that ends with nuclear war."
