          "content": "### PROFILE: ROBERT F. KENNEDY (RFK)\n**Attorney General**\n\nRFK has become the moral compass of the 'Dove' faction. While the Generals talk about sortie rates and kill probabilities, RFK talks about history and the soul of the nation.\n\n**The Moral Argument:**\nRFK passes a note to his brother: *'I now know how Tojo felt when he was planning Pearl Harbor.'* He argues that for the United States—a champion of freedom—to launch a surprise Sunday morning attack on a small island nation would be a betrayal of its heritage. The world would view us as bullies and aggressors.\n\n**The 'Golden Bridge':**\nRFK pushes for the Blockade (Quarantine) because it offers Khrushchev a 'Golden Bridge'—a way to retreat without humiliation. If we bomb the Soviet technicians, Khrushchev *must* retaliate to save face. If we stop his ships, he has a choice. The Blockade shifts the burden of the decision from Washington to Moscow."
