          "content": "### THE ESCALATION LADDER\n\n**ExComm Analysis:**\nThe intelligence assessment is grim. The shootdown of Major Anderson is a clear escalation. The 'Escalation Ladder'—the strategic theory that conflicts proceed in predictable steps—has been kicked over. We are no longer in a crisis; we are in a combat zone.\n\n**The Pentagon's Position:**\nThe Joint Chiefs are demanding authorization to execute the Standing Orders. General LeMay argues that the Soviets are testing American resolve. He states: 'They have fired the first shot. If we do not return fire, they will take Berlin next.' The jets in Florida are armed with napalm and high explosives. The pilots are in their cockpits. They are waiting for one word from the White House.\n\n**The President's Dilemma:**\nKennedy is hesitant. He is looking at the photos of the wreckage. He suspects this might not be a deliberate order from Khrushchev, but rather a panic reaction by a local Soviet commander. But can he take that risk? If he cancels the airstrike, he is effectively telling the Soviets that they can shoot down American planes with impunity. He is 'eating' the loss of a brave pilot. It is political suicide. But striking back might trigger the nuclear warheads we know are on the island. The red phone is silent."
