          "content": "### THE TALE OF TWO LETTERS\n\nIn the final hours, the White House receives two conflicting messages from Moscow.\n\n**Letter #1 (The 'Soft' Letter):**\nReceived Friday night. It is long, rambling, emotional, and clearly written by Khrushchev himself. It speaks of the 'knot of war' and offers to remove the missiles if the US simply promises not to invade Cuba.\n\n**Letter #2 (The 'Hard' Letter):**\nReceived Saturday morning (broadcast publicly on Radio Moscow). It is stiff, formal, and likely written by the Politburo. It adds a new, impossible condition: The US must remove its Jupiter missiles from Turkey in exchange for the Soviet withdrawal.\n\n**The 'Trollope Ploy':**\nExComm is paralyzed. How do we respond? Attorney General RFK suggests a brilliant diplomatic maneuver (later named after a plot device in Anthony Trollope novels): **We ignore the second letter and answer only the first.** We accept the 'non-invasion' pledge and pretend the Turkey demand was never made."
